You need to provide the element type as method parameter and use [TypeFactory][1], more precisely [TypeFactory.constructCollectionType(collectionClass, elementClass)][2] to build the `JavaType` dynamically at runtime.

Additionally i would suggest to use `InputStream` as the parameter, it&#39;s more generic and you can use the method with basically anything (file streams, you can convert text to streams, other streams).
```
public class Test {

  public static void main(String[] args) {
    try (FileInputStream stream = new FileInputStream(&quot;path-to-file&quot;)) {
      List&lt;A&gt; aList = readAsList(stream, A.class);
      System.out.println(aList);
    } catch (IOException exc) {
      exc.printStackTrace();
    }
  }

  private static &lt;T&gt; List&lt;T&gt; readAsList(InputStream inputStream, Class&lt;T&gt; elementType) throws IOException {
    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    TypeFactory factory = TypeFactory.defaultInstance();
    return mapper.readValue(inputStream, factory.constructCollectionType(List.class, elementType));
  }

  private static class A {
  }

  private static class B {
  }
}
```

  [1]: https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-databind/javadoc/2.7/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/type/TypeFactory.html
  [2]: https://fasterxml.github.io/jackson-databind/javadoc/2.7/com/fasterxml/jackson/databind/type/TypeFactory.html#constructCollectionType(java.lang.Class,%20java.lang.Class)

